@MarcusButler Let‚Äôs duel

I liken these crazes to NFTs.

Some are for trading.
Some can be used for staking or battling with complete random odds. 

What's missing is CrazyBones.
Purely skill driven, winner takes all PvP.

Oh, and make it fully interoperable.

Next summer we got CrazyBones.

You stand a couple meters apart from your opponent. Then you throw your CrazyBone at your opponents. The first to knock the others down would win BOTH crazy bones.

It got banned very quickly. But the thrill was wild!
Purely skill.

Then came BeyBlades.
Real-time battling, almost totally chance driven. 
Winner kept the blade chip. 

That was thrilling but not as addictive because there was no clear skill involved. https://t.co/LgFgq5uszK

As a kid, each summer there would be this new craze that swept the playground.
Pokemon was first. 
It was about trading, pre-internet, trying to work out what cards were rarer or broker deals based on demand and supply at your school.

We wrote a contract allowing two users to enter into a 'fight'. 

Their NFTs avatars are sent to holding contract. 
They fight in a real-time game of skill.
Smash/kart/chess for example. 

The winner of the fight receives both NFTs.

Spectators of this area scream as they watch.

Got off the phone with legal.

Battle for pink slips incoming. 

Who dares?
